WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.120
Okay, Paul, you gave me a tough act to follow

00:00:03.120 --> 00:00:07.420
with that demo, but we'll try nonetheless.

00:00:07.420 --> 00:00:10.070
So I'm Ronan, great to be here, my

00:00:10.070 --> 00:00:14.580
first Atmosphere Conf, hopefully the first of many.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:16.880
And I'm here to talk about trails.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:19.770
So we're in the Pacific Northwest, we all love the

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:20.600
outdoors.

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:22.890
Two thirds of Sembol are Vancouver natives, so we're

00:00:22.890 --> 00:00:24.240
kind of made in Vancouver.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:26.230
And maybe I can move here, I'm trying to escape

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:27.860
the United States at this point.

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:28.860
Off record.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:32.890
So this talk is going to be about rediscovering the

00:00:32.940 --> 00:00:35.230
magic of trails online.

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:37.990
We draw a lot of inspiration from trails as a metaphor for

00:00:38.090 --> 00:00:41.230
our digital lives and connecting a lot to the themes that Aaron

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:43.570
Kassane was talking about in the morning.

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:46.720
We have this problem, before we start with a problem,

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:48.780
we have serendipity online, right?

00:00:48.780 --> 00:00:52.130
We have aha moments that really change the way we see the

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:52.810
world.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.610
And I want people here to think for a second of some

00:00:55.610 --> 00:00:59.110
of your aha moments and think if they came from information that

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:00.160
you found online.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:02.790
And raise your hand if those aha moments that you come across

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:03.930
are like online sourced.

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:05.100
Okay.

00:01:05.100 --> 00:01:06.100
Cool.

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:08.610
Lots of people getting serendipity online.

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:17.040
Now think of your everyday browsing experience.

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:19.330
And I want you to raise your hand if it looks something

00:01:19.460 --> 00:01:20.040
like this.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.040
Come on.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:22.040
Yeah.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:23.040
Okay.

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:24.040
So...

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:25.040
More tabs.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:26.040
Yeah.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:28.260
So this is the brilliance and brokenness of the web

00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:28.480
.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:31.630
We have these genuine moments of insight, but they are far

00:01:31.630 --> 00:01:36.130
outweighed by this routine sense of overwhelm.

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:38.130
Is this just the way things are?

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.630
Is it a law of nature that we have to learn to

00:01:40.630 --> 00:01:41.480
live with?

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:44.920
Or can we make aha moments probable and not just possible?

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:47.430
Well, we think we can, and also that there has

00:01:47.530 --> 00:01:49.330
never been a better time for it.

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.100
To understand how, though, we'll need to understand how

00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:55.730
we even got here in the first place.

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:58.350
So the early web was like a new frontier.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:00.520
It was a big, unspoiled commons, open

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:02.770
trails, serendipitous discovery.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:05.660
But it was also wild, challenging.

00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:09.430
It was hard to navigate, hard to add to, and

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:11.550
underdeveloped.

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:14.910
Web 2 is the age of attention superhighways, which

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:17.510
we unfortunately are still living in.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:18.940
Platforms give us scale.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:20.080
They bring everyone online.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:22.370
They make it easy to find and create content.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:25.320
But they also paved over all those trails with the superhigh

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:28.500
way that you pay for with your attention and only takes you

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:31.040
where the platform wants you to go.

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:33.930
Your likes feed the algorithm.

00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:35.010
Platforms constrain our behavior.

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:38.660
They make us predictable like rats in a Skinner box.

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:43.090
Our bookmarks are piling up unused.

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:48.280
And yeah, the tab problem is still unresolved.

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:51.170
Instead of feeding algorithms or hoarding bookmarks, with Sem

00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:55.290
ble we're working on an alternative paradigm: collective human-

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:56.970
driven mapping.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
What if we could create trail networks together?

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.780
Semble lets you leave online trail markers for yourself and for

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:04.700
others.

00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:07.760
Our logo is a cairn, those small stone stacks

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:11.050
hikers spontaneously build to mark trails.

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:13.000
If you've ever been out hiking and lost a path,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.940
you know how great it feels to find one of these.

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:19.290
And we're trying to bring that feeling online.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:23.750
We call Semble a social knowledge network.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:27.320
It's a social tool for creating.

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:29.310
I have to do this in Figma.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:31.310
Is this going to work?

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:33.310
Oh, there we go.

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:34.320
Okay.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:35.320
How many of you have actually used Semble?

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:36.320
Oh, wow.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:37.320
Cool.

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:38.320
It's always surprising.

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:39.320
Great.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:46.440
So you know the basics, a lot of you.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:50.260
It's a tool for creating and discovering your knowledge trails.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.960
And trails are really any kind of content you find meaningful or

00:03:53.050 --> 00:03:53.640
interesting.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:54.700
Oh, this is...

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:55.700
Okay.

00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:56.700
Yeah.

00:03:56.700 --> 00:03:59.700
There's some good security here.

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:00.700
Okay.

00:04:00.700 --> 00:04:01.700
So, yeah.

00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:04.760
The basic units of Semble are cards and collections.

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:07.780
The basic activity is bookmarking links and adding them to

00:04:07.780 --> 00:04:08.540
collections.

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:11.010
And we call those bookmarks cards.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:13.740
Everything in Semble is on app proto.

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:16.760
Here we're creating a collection.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:20.290
You can create private collections that only you can add to,

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:25.380
or you can create open collections that anyone can add to.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:28.580
And how do we move this?

00:04:29.420 --> 00:04:30.600
Cool.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:34.980
On the discovery side, we can show you also...

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:38.180
We have an explore feed that shows you recent activity from other

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:38.710
users.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:42.070
So you can see what other people are adding.

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.410
And you can see for each link, the number there,

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:48.280
like that plus four, how many people have added it.

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:49.640
We also have a search page.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:52.840
So you can just search the Semble knowledge for anything you

00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:54.050
're interested in.

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:57.490
Here is me searching for AI coding agents, a popular topic

00:04:57.560 --> 00:04:57.780
.

00:04:57.780 --> 00:04:58.810
I didn't do this.

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:01.710
This is before I knew about Paul's demo.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:02.740
We detect link types.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:06.090
So you can filter your search to show different media types.

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:11.900
So you have research, audio, video, books, whatever

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:12.090
.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:14.440
And the cool thing about this is it's community curated knowledge

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:14.570
.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:16.000
So it's high signal.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
It's not slop.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.040
It's things that people found valuable.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:22.810
And as Semble grows, then it'll just become more

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:24.160
valuable.

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:26.670
One of the other key features of Semble is what we

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:27.930
call the Semble page.

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:30.850
So the Semble page is an overlay.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:33.750
And right now you're looking at a paper on science.

00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:36.530
This was a pretty popular paper.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:38.700
A lot of people are talking about it.

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:40.060
What we're missing here is what I said before.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:41.200
We don't have any context.

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:42.340
What are people saying about this paper?

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:43.340
Is it true?

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:47.460
A lot of big claims on human performance and talent acquisition.

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:50.180
But what is the juice behind it?

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:52.400
So the Semble page is that overlay layer.

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:53.400
You click on a button.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:54.400
You get to the Semble page.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.240
Any URL has this.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:59.460
And here is where you can see context from AppProto

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:00.460
and beyond, eventually.

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:02.380
There are a bunch of tabs here.

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:03.600
I'm not going to show you everything.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:05.900
It's just a lightning talk.

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.520
We have mentions on BlueSky and on Leaflet.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:12.240
We have collections in Semble that it's been added to

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:13.930
, notes people have created.

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:19.150
We have an especially cool feature that we're just really launching

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:21.840
in the next few days, connections.

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:24.040
So this is the tab I'm on right now.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.330
Connections are a way to connect to URLs and let you

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.440
say something about that connection.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:30.950
So here, for example, I saw a really great comment

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:32.700
on BlueSky about this paper.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.340
And I want people to be aware of it when they look

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:36.370
at this paper so I can make that connection and say this

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:37.260
was helpful context.

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:40.150
So it's kind of like community notes, but for any

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:41.600
URL and for any note.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.490
And we're really excited to see how y'all are

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:45.820
going to use it.

00:06:45.820 --> 00:06:48.390
We also have some cool notifications in Semble that are a

00:06:48.430 --> 00:06:49.850
bit different than BlueSky.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:53.640
So for example, you get notified if someone makes a connection

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:55.740
to a card in your library.

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:57.860
That's kind of cool because it's instead of, yeah

00:06:57.860 --> 00:06:59.760
, it's you're adding your cards and then you're

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:01.810
starting to see how other people build on the knowledge you're

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:02.260
adding.

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:06.580
And it's a really interesting way to come across new links

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:06.810
.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:09.770
We also have following, but for collections.

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:11.630
We call it faceted following and we think it's really

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:15.230
interesting because it gives you a signal for specific kinds of content

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:16.570
that people are interested in.

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:18.530
So maybe you're creating a bunch of stuff, but you

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:19.880
see what people are following.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:22.540
Maybe they're following your cat video collection, or maybe they

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:24.380
're following your research collection.

00:07:24.380 --> 00:07:26.670
But it gives you the idea of what are people actually interested

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:31.350
in instead of just like your general stream of content.

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:32.420
Why now?

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:34.930
Well, we think we're in a unique moment, as

00:07:35.030 --> 00:07:36.640
Paul was talking about.

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:40.290
And this unique moment is making all our work more urgent and

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.180
more important, we think.

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:45.940
Because, yeah, the combination of AI and social networks brings

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:48.550
great risks and great opportunities.

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:52.140
The value of authentic human connection is going to skyrocket as

00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:55.870
AI companies are really going to try to mine our attention and

00:07:55.870 --> 00:08:00.050
build browsers that are going to record everything we do.

00:08:00.060 --> 00:08:02.950
The bright side of this is that AppRoto lets us

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:06.380
gain meaningful ownership of our attention.

00:08:06.380 --> 00:08:10.790
And this also helps us answer some of the questions people might

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:14.050
have at this point, which is, haven't we already

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:17.100
tried to build these annotation tools before?

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:19.840
We have, and there are a lot of different annotation apps

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:22.220
, but what is truly new is a post-app annotation

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:23.220
app.

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.920
This is a meme that hangs by my bed.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:29.210
It doesn't really, but if I was a person who

00:08:29.340 --> 00:08:31.730
hung things by my bed, it would hang there.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:34.770
The idea is that the killer app for AppRoto isn

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:37.060
't an app, it's the ecosystem.

00:08:37.060 --> 00:08:40.520
And we're starting to see early signs of this.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:43.270
A great example is our interop with Margin, which

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:46.890
is another popular AppRoto annotation tool.

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:51.400
And we've also been plotting various interop schemes with many

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:53.630
of you here in the audience.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:55.660
So the way the Margin Semble interop works is

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:57.840
when you're on Margin, you see Semble activity

00:08:57.840 --> 00:08:59.880
, and when you're on Semble, you see Mar

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:00.670
gin activity.

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:02.990
It's kind of simple, but also kind of magical,

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:04.450
and people really love it.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:06.540
If you look carefully, you can also see one of Cameron

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:08.970
's AI agents making annotations there.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.340
We live in exciting times.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.590
Alongside interop, another really unique part about building in

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:18.820
AppRoto is just the tinkering and hacking energy

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:19.140
here.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:22.420
I absolutely cannot do justice to it in the time I have

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.920
, but I'll just share a few examples.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:27.940
One really cool pattern we've seen developing is living libraries.

00:09:27.940 --> 00:09:31.670
So people are putting their personal link libraries on protocol.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:34.740
These are, yeah, just a few pages.

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:36.730
Nick Vincent here has done a literature review.

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:39.740
It's like a living literature review backed by Semble.

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:42.250
So he adds things to collections on Semble, and they

00:09:42.350 --> 00:09:45.240
appear on this cool library that people can search through.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:47.710
And it's just, yeah, really exciting because, for

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:49.740
example, it can be collectively curated.

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:51.340
And a bunch of people can add to these, and they

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:52.490
don't need to touch the HTML.

00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:56.950
They don't need to do get pull requests to the repository

00:09:57.040 --> 00:09:57.340
.

00:09:57.340 --> 00:10:01.070
People have also been creating really cool fusion between Semble and

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:05.300
tools for thought like Obsidian.

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:08.460
We actually, yeah, it's starting to become a thing

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:08.760
.

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.650
People are very excited by the opportunity to connect their personal knowledge

00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:16.540
tools in new ways using AppRoto.

00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:20.140
Another wonderful emergent pattern has been collectively curated Semble collections

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:20.300
.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:21.590
Shout out to Chris.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:23.740
I don't know if he's still in the room.

00:10:23.740 --> 00:10:24.740
Maybe not.

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:25.740
Okay.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:27.650
Chris Shank has started the @news, which is power

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:29.240
ing the atmospheric weather report.

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:33.440
And there's several regular contributors here that are adding interesting links

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:35.740
, and they're collecting that.

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:37.580
And I want to end, I know Boris, you're

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:38.630
signaling to me.

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:41.170
I want to end this talk with a thought about how we

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:43.470
can build a brighter future together.

00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:46.510
So, information overload, one way to think about it,

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:51.120
is the result of a linear attention economy.

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:54.320
Information consumes our attention, and the more information that becomes available

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:56.800
, the more our attention is consumed.

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:01.310
Semble and @proto let us create circular attention economies

00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:01.610
.

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:04.700
Attention economies where we not only consume, they don't,

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:09.010
information doesn't only consume our attention, but we actually share

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:12.430
our attention traces, as you can see over here.

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:15.560
We share our attention traces, and by doing so, we

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:18.350
help other people navigate information.

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:20.090
And this is kind of like upcycling, which is

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:22.800
why I put this picture here of a community garden that I

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:27.690
really like in Berlin, where people took shoes and they started

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:30.940
planting plants in them.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:32.930
And when we share our attention online, we're letting other

00:11:32.930 --> 00:11:35.990
people reuse our attention in interesting ways, and helping them navigate

00:11:35.990 --> 00:11:39.490
information overload together, creating the trails that we need to,

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:43.620
yeah, live online in this age of crazy information overload.

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:44.960
Thank you.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:49.770
Thank you.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:54.510
And you also happen to organize @Science.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:55.640
That too, yes.

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:57.300
I'm going to sleep well tonight, yeah.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:12:01.480
I'm done with all my APROTO obligations,

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:03.020
but it's- Amazing.

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:04.020
Yes.

